# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ridge-lasso-regression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] In statistics and machine learning, the **bias–variance tradeoff** describes the relationship between a model's complexity, the accuracy of its predictions, and how well it can make predictions on previously unseen data that were not used to train the model.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] In general, as the number of tunable parameters in a model increases, it becomes more flexible, and can better fit a training data set.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] That is, the model has lower error or lower bias.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] However, for more flexible models, there will tend to be greater **variance** to the model fit each time we take a set of samples to create a new training data set.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] It is said that there is greater variance in the model's estimated parameters.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The **bias–variance decomposition** is a way of analyzing a learning algorithm's expected generalization error with respect to a particular problem as a sum of three terms, the bias, variance, and a quantity called the *irreducible error*, resulting from noise in the problem itself.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] For each trial, a few noisy data points are provided as a training set (top).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] For a wide spread (image 2) the bias is high: the RBFs cannot fully approximate the function (especially the central dip), but the variance between different trials is low.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] As spread decreases (image 3 and 4) the bias decreases: the blue curves more closely approximate the red.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] However, depending on the noise in different trials the variance between trials increases.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] In the lowermost image the approximated values for x=0 varies wildly depending on where the data points were located.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The bias–variance tradeoff is a central problem in supervised learning.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Ideally, one wants to choose a model that both accurately captures the regularities in its training data, but also generalizes well to unseen data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Unfortunately, it is typically impossible to do both simultaneously.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] High-variance learning methods may be able to represent their training set well but are at risk of overfitting to noisy or unrepresentative training data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] In contrast, algorithms with high bias typically produce simpler models that may fail to capture important regularities (i.e. underfit) in the data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] It is an often made fallacy to assume that complex models must have high variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] High variance models are "complex" in some sense, but the reverse need not be true.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] In addition, one has to be careful how to define complexity.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] In particular, the number of parameters used to describe the model is a poor measure of complexity.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The model $f_{a,b}(x)=a\sin(bx)$ has only two parameters ( $a,b$ ) but it can interpolate any number of points by oscillating with a high enough frequency, resulting in both a high bias and high variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] An analogy can be made to the relationship between accuracy and precision.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Accuracy is one way of quantifying bias and can intuitively be improved by selecting from only local information.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Consequently, a sample will appear accurate (i.e. have low bias) under the aforementioned selection conditions, but may result in underfitting.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] In other words, test data may not agree as closely with training data, which would indicate imprecision and therefore inflated variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] A graphical example would be a straight line fit to data exhibiting quadratic behavior overall.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Precision is a description of variance and generally can only be improved by selecting information from a comparatively larger space.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The option to select many data points over a broad sample space is the ideal condition for any analysis.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] However, intrinsic constraints (whether physical, theoretical, computational, etc.) will always play a limiting role.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The limiting case where only a finite number of data points are selected over a broad sample space may result in improved precision and lower variance overall, but may also result in an overreliance on the training data (overfitting).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] This means that test data would also not agree as closely with the training data, but in this case the reason is inaccuracy or high bias.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] To borrow from the previous example, the graphical representation would appear as a high-order polynomial fit to the same data exhibiting quadratic behavior.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Note that error in each case is measured the same way, but the reason ascribed to the error is different depending on the balance between bias and variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] To mitigate how much information is used from neighboring observations, a model can be smoothed via explicit regularization, such as shrinkage.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Suppose that we have a training set consisting of a set of points $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ and real-valued labels $y_{i}$ associated with the points $x_{i}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] We assume that the data is generated by a function $f(x)$ such as $y=f(x)+\varepsilon$ , where the noise, $\varepsilon$ , has zero mean and unit variance $\sigma ^{2}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] We want to find a function ${\hat {f}}\!(x;D)$ , that approximates the true function $f(x)$ as well as possible, by means of some learning algorithm based on a training dataset (sample) $D=\{(x_{1},y_{1})\dots ,(x_{n},y_{n})\}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] We make "as well as possible" precise by measuring the mean squared error between y and ${\hat {f}}\!(x;D)$ : we want $(y-{\hat {f}}\!(x;D))^{2}$ to be minimal, both for $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ *and for points outside of our sample*.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Of course, we cannot hope to do so perfectly, since the $y_{i}$ contain noise $\varepsilon$ ; this means we must be prepared to accept an *irreducible error* in any function we come up with.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Finding an ${\hat {f}}$ that generalizes to points outside of the training set can be done with any of the countless algorithms used for supervised learning.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The expectation ranges over different choices of the training set $D=\{(x_{1},y_{1})\dots ,(x_{n},y_{n})\}$ , all sampled from the same joint distribution $P(x,y)$ which can for example be done via bootstrapping.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Since all three terms are non-negative, the irreducible error forms a lower bound on the expected error on unseen samples.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The more complex the model ${\hat {f}}\!(x)$ is, the more data points it will capture, and the lower the bias will be.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] However, complexity will make the model "move" more to capture the data points, and hence its variance will be larger.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The derivation of the bias–variance decomposition for squared error proceeds as follows.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] For convenience, we drop the D subscript in the following lines, such that ${\hat {f}}\!(x;D)={\hat {f}}\!(x)$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Moreover, the third term of this equation is nothing but $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] This last series of equalities comes from the fact that $f(x)$ is not a random variable, but a fixed, deterministic function of x .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Dimensionality reduction and feature selection can decrease variance by simplifying models.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Similarly, a larger training set tends to decrease variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Adding features (predictors) tends to decrease bias, at the expense of introducing additional variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] One way of resolving the trade-off is to use mixture models and ensemble learning.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] For example, boosting combines many "weak" (high bias) models in an ensemble that has lower bias than the individual models, while bagging combines "strong" learners in a way that reduces their variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Model validation methods such as cross-validation (statistics) can be used to tune models so as to optimize the trade-off.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] where $N_{1}(x),\dots ,N_{k}(x)$ are the k nearest neighbors of x in the training set.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The bias (first term) is a monotone rising function of k, while the variance (second term) drops off as k is increased.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] In fact, under "reasonable assumptions" the bias of the first-nearest neighbor (1-NN) estimator vanishes entirely as the size of the training set approaches infinity.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The bias–variance decomposition forms the conceptual basis for regression regularization methods such as LASSO and ridge regression.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Regularization methods introduce bias into the regression solution that can reduce variance considerably relative to the ordinary least squares (OLS) solution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Although the OLS solution provides non-biased regression estimates, the lower variance solutions produced by regularization techniques provide superior MSE performance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The bias–variance decomposition was originally formulated for least-squares regression.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] For the case of classification under the 0-1 loss (misclassification rate), it is possible to find a similar decomposition, with the caveat that the variance term becomes dependent on the target label.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Alternatively, if the classification problem can be phrased as probabilistic classification, then the expected cross-entropy can instead be decomposed to give bias and variance terms with the same semantics but taking a different form.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Even though the bias–variance decomposition does not directly apply in reinforcement learning, a similar tradeoff can also characterize generalization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] When an agent has limited information on its environment, the suboptimality of an RL algorithm can be decomposed into the sum of two terms: a term related to an asymptotic bias and a term due to overfitting.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The asymptotic bias is directly related to the learning algorithm (independently of the quantity of data) while the overfitting term comes from the fact that the amount of data is limited.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] While in traditional Monte Carlo methods the bias is typically zero, modern approaches, such as Markov chain Monte Carlo are only asymptotically unbiased, at best.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] While widely discussed in the context of machine learning, the bias–variance dilemma has been examined in the context of human cognition, most notably by Gerd Gigerenzer and co-workers in the context of learned heuristics.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] They have argued (see references below) that the human brain resolves the dilemma in the case of the typically sparse, poorly-characterized training-sets provided by experience by adopting high-bias/low variance heuristics.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] This reflects the fact that a zero-bias approach has poor generalizability to new situations, and also unreasonably presumes precise knowledge of the true state of the world.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] The resulting heuristics are relatively simple, but produce better inferences in a wider variety of situations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] Geman et al. argue that the bias–variance dilemma implies that abilities such as generic object recognition cannot be learned from scratch, but require a certain degree of "hard wiring" that is later tuned by experience.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/bias-variance-tradeoff] This is because model-free approaches to inference require impractically large training sets if they are to avoid high variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The lasso method assumes that the coefficients of the linear model are sparse, meaning that few of them are non-zero.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] It was originally introduced in geophysics, and later by Robert Tibshirani, who coined the term.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso was originally formulated for linear regression models.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] This simple case reveals a substantial amount about the estimator.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] These include its relationship to ridge regression and best subset selection and the connections between lasso coefficient estimates and so-called soft thresholding.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] It also reveals that (like standard linear regression) the coefficient estimates do not need to be unique if covariates are collinear.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Though originally defined for linear regression, lasso regularization is easily extended to other statistical models including generalized linear models, generalized estimating equations, proportional hazards models, and M-estimators.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso's ability to perform subset selection relies on the form of the constraint and has a variety of interpretations including in terms of geometry, Bayesian statistics and convex analysis.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The LASSO is closely related to basis pursuit denoising.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso was introduced in order to improve the prediction accuracy and interpretability of regression models.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] It selects a reduced set of the known covariates for use in a model.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso was developed independently in geophysics literature in 1986, based on prior work that used the $\ell ^{1}$ penalty for both fitting and penalization of the coefficients.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Statistician Robert Tibshirani independently rediscovered and popularized it in 1996, based on Breiman's nonnegative garrote.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Prior to lasso, the most widely used method for choosing covariates was stepwise selection.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] That approach only improves prediction accuracy in certain cases, such as when only a few covariates have a strong relationship with the outcome.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] However, in other cases, it can increase prediction error.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] At the time, ridge regression was the most popular technique for improving prediction accuracy.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Ridge regression improves prediction error by shrinking the sum of the squares of the regression coefficients to be less than a fixed value in order to reduce overfitting, but it does not perform covariate selection and therefore does not help to make the model more interpretable.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso achieves both of these goals by forcing the sum of the absolute value of the regression coefficients to be less than a fixed value, which forces certain coefficients to zero, excluding them from impacting prediction.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] This idea is similar to ridge regression, which also shrinks the size of the coefficients; however, ridge regression does not set coefficients to zero (and, thus, does not perform variable selection).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Consider a sample consisting of *N* cases, each of which consists of *p* covariates and a single outcome.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Here $\beta _{0}$ is the constant coefficient, $\beta :=(\beta _{1},\beta _{2},\ldots ,\beta _{p})$ is the coefficient vector, and t is a prespecified free parameter that determines the degree of regularization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Additionally, the covariates are typically standardized ${\textstyle {\bigl (}\sum _{i=1}^{N}x_{i}^{2}=1{\bigr )}}$ so that the solution does not depend on the measurement scale.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Some basic properties of the lasso estimator can now be considered.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Ridge regression shrinks all coefficients by a uniform factor of $\ (1+N\lambda )^{-1}\$ and does not set any coefficients to zero.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Therefore, the lasso estimates share features of both ridge and best subset selection regression since they both shrink the magnitude of all the coefficients, like ridge regression and set some of them to zero, as in the best subset selection case.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Additionally, while ridge regression scales all of the coefficients by a constant factor, lasso instead translates the coefficients towards zero by a constant value and sets them to zero if they reach it.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In one special case two covariates, say *j* and *k*, are identical for each observation, so that $x_{(j)}=x_{(k)}$ , where $x_{(j),i}=x_{(k),i}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Then the values of $\beta _{j}$ and $\beta _{k}$ that minimize the lasso objective function are not uniquely determined.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Several variants of the lasso, including the Elastic net regularization, have been designed to address this shortcoming.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso regularization can be extended to other objective functions such as those for generalized linear models, generalized estimating equations, proportional hazards models, and M-estimators.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso can set coefficients to zero, while the superficially similar ridge regression cannot.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] This is due to the difference in the shape of their constraint boundaries.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The lasso can be rescaled so that it becomes easy to anticipate and influence the degree of shrinkage associated with a given value of $\lambda$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] It is assumed that X is standardized with z-scores and that y is centered (zero mean).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Let $\beta _{0}$ represent the hypothesized regression coefficients and let $b_{\text{OLS}}$ refer to the data-optimized ordinary least squares solutions.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] We can then define the Lagrangian as a tradeoff between the in-sample accuracy of the data-optimized solutions and the simplicity of sticking to the hypothesized values.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The first fraction represents relative accuracy, the second fraction relative simplicity, and $\lambda$ balances between the two.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Given a single regressor, relative simplicity can be defined by specifying $q_{i}$ as $|b_{\text{OLS}}-\beta _{0}|$ , which is the maximum amount of deviation from $\beta _{0}$ when $\lambda =0$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The hypothesized value of $\beta _{0}=0$ is selected if $\lambda$ is bigger than $R^{2}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Furthermore, if $R^{2}=1$ , then $\lambda$ represents the proportional influence of $\beta _{0}=0$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In other words, $\lambda \times 100\%$ measures in percentage terms the minimal amount of influence of the hypothesized value relative to the data-optimized OLS solution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Given multiple regressors, the moment that a parameter is activated (i.e. allowed to deviate from $\beta _{0}$ ) is also determined by a regressor's contribution to $R^{2}$ accuracy.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] First, $R^{2}=1-{\frac {(y-Xb)'(y-Xb)}{(y-X\beta _{0})'(y-X\beta _{0})}}.$ An $R^{2}$ of 75% means that in-sample accuracy improves by 75% if the unrestricted OLS solutions are used instead of the hypothesized $\beta _{0}$ values.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] If $b=b_{\text{OLS}}$ when $R^{2}$ is computed, then the diagonal elements of $R^{\otimes }$ sum to $R^{2}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The diagonal $R^{\otimes }$ values may be smaller than 0 or, less often, larger than 1.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] If regressors are uncorrelated, then the $i^{th}$ diagonal element of $R^{\otimes }$ simply corresponds to the $r^{2}$ value between $x_{i}$ and y .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] A rescaled version of the adaptive lasso of can be obtained by setting $q_{{\mbox{adaptive lasso}},i}=|b_{{\text{OLS}},i}-\beta _{0,i}|$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] If regressors are uncorrelated, the moment that the $i^{th}$ parameter is activated is given by the $i^{th}$ diagonal element of $R^{\otimes }$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Even when regressors are correlated, the first time that a regression parameter is activated occurs when $\lambda$ is equal to the highest diagonal element of $R^{\otimes }$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] These results can be compared to a rescaled version of the lasso by defining $q_{{\mbox{lasso}},i}={\frac {1}{p}}\sum _{l}|b_{{\text{OLS}},l}-\beta _{0,l}|$ , which is the average absolute deviation of $b_{\text{OLS}}$ from $\beta _{0}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] For $p=1$ , the moment of activation is again given by ${\tilde {\lambda }}_{{\text{lasso}},i}=R^{2}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] If $\beta _{0}$ is a vector of zeros and a subset of $p_{B}$ relevant parameters are equally responsible for a perfect fit of $R^{2}=1$ , then this subset is activated at a $\lambda$ value of ${\frac {1}{p}}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In other words, the inclusion of irrelevant regressors delays the moment that relevant regressors are activated by this rescaled lasso.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The adaptive lasso and the lasso are special cases of a '1ASTc' estimator.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The latter only groups parameters together if the absolute correlation among regressors is larger than a user-specified value.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Just as ridge regression can be interpreted as linear regression for which the coefficients have been assigned normal prior distributions, lasso can be interpreted as linear regression for which the coefficients have Laplace prior distributions.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The Laplace distribution is sharply peaked at zero (its first derivative is discontinuous at zero) and it concentrates its probability mass closer to zero than does the normal distribution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] This provides an alternative explanation of why lasso tends to set some coefficients to zero, while ridge regression does not.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso can also be viewed as a convex relaxation of the best subset selection regression problem, which is to find the subset of $\leq k$ covariates that results in the smallest value of the objective function for some fixed $k\leq n$ , where n is the total number of covariates.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso variants have been created in order to remedy limitations of the original technique and to make the method more useful for particular problems.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Almost all of these focus on respecting or exploiting dependencies among the covariates.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Elastic net regularization adds an additional ridge regression-like penalty that improves performance when the number of predictors is larger than the sample size, allows the method to select strongly correlated variables together, and improves overall prediction accuracy.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Group lasso allows groups of related covariates to be selected as a single unit, which can be useful in settings where it does not make sense to include some covariates without others.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Further extensions of group lasso perform variable selection within individual groups (sparse group lasso) and allow overlap between groups (overlap group lasso).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Fused lasso can account for the spatial or temporal characteristics of a problem, resulting in estimates that better match system structure.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso-regularized models can be fit using techniques including subgradient methods, least-angle regression (LARS), and proximal gradient methods.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Determining the optimal value for the regularization parameter is an important part of ensuring that the model performs well; it is typically chosen using cross-validation.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In 2005, Zou and Hastie introduced the elastic net.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] When *p* > *n* (the number of covariates is greater than the sample size) lasso can select only *n* covariates (even when more are associated with the outcome) and it tends to select one covariate from any set of highly correlated covariates.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Additionally, even when *n* > *p*, ridge regression tends to perform better given strongly correlated covariates.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] So the result of the elastic net penalty is a combination of the effects of the lasso and ridge penalties.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Returning to the general case, the fact that the penalty function is now strictly convex means that if $x_{(j)}=x_{(k)}$ , ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}={\hat {\beta }}_{k}$ , which is a change from lasso.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Therefore, highly correlated covariates tend to have similar regression coefficients, with the degree of similarity depending on both $\|y\|_{1}$ and $\lambda _{2}$ , which is different from lasso.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] This phenomenon, in which strongly correlated covariates have similar regression coefficients, is referred to as the grouping effect.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Grouping is desirable since, in applications such as tying genes to a disease, finding all the associated covariates is preferable, rather than selecting one from each set of correlated covariates, as lasso often does.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In addition, selecting only one from each group typically results in increased prediction error, since the model is less robust (which is why ridge regression often outperforms lasso).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In 2006, Yuan and Lin introduced the group lasso to allow predefined groups of covariates to jointly be selected into or out of a model.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] This is useful in many settings, perhaps most obviously when a categorical variable is coded as a collection of binary covariates.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In this case, group lasso can ensure that all the variables encoding the categorical covariate are included or excluded together.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Another setting in which grouping is natural is in biological studies.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Since genes and proteins often lie in known pathways, which pathways are related to an outcome may be more significant than whether individual genes are.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Additionally, the penalty term is now a sum over $\ell ^{2}$ norms defined by the positive definite matrices $K_{j}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] If each covariate is in its own group and $K_{j}=I$ , then this reduces to the standard lasso, while if there is only a single group and $K_{1}=I$ , it reduces to ridge regression.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Since the penalty reduces to an $\ell ^{2}$ norm on the subspaces defined by each group, it cannot select out only some of the covariates from a group, just as ridge regression cannot.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] However, because the penalty is the sum over the different subspace norms, as in the standard lasso, the constraint has some non-differential points, which correspond to some subspaces being identically zero.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Therefore, it can set the coefficient vectors corresponding to some subspaces to zero, while only shrinking others.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] However, it is possible to extend the group lasso to the so-called sparse group lasso, which can select individual covariates within a group, by adding an additional $\ell ^{1}$ penalty to each group subspace.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Another extension, group lasso with overlap allows covariates to be shared across groups, e.g., if a gene were to occur in two pathways.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The "gglasso" package by in R, allows for fast and efficient implementation of Group LASSO.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In some cases, the phenomenon under study may have important spatial or temporal structure that must be considered during analysis, such as time series or image-based data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In 2005, Tibshirani and colleagues introduced the fused lasso to extend the use of lasso to this type of data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The first constraint is the lasso constraint, while the second directly penalizes large changes with respect to the temporal or spatial structure, which forces the coefficients to vary smoothly to reflect the system's underlying logic.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Clustered lasso is a generalization of fused lasso that identifies and groups relevant covariates based on their effects (coefficients).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The basic idea is to penalize the differences between the coefficients so that nonzero ones cluster.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In contrast, variables can be clustered into highly correlated groups, and then a single representative covariate can be extracted from each cluster.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Algorithms exist that solve the fused lasso problem, and some generalizations of it.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Algorithms can solve it exactly in a finite number of operations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Lasso, elastic net, group and fused lasso construct the penalty functions from the $\ell ^{1}$ and $\ell ^{2}$ norms (with weights, if necessary).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The bridge regression utilises general $\ell ^{p}$ norms ( $p\geq 1$ ) and quasinorms ( $0<p<1$ ).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] It is claimed that the fractional quasi-norms $\ell ^{p}$ ( $0<p<1$ ) provide more meaningful results in data analysis both theoretically and empirically.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The non-convexity of these quasi-norms complicates the optimization problem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The efficient algorithm for minimization is based on piece-wise quadratic approximation of subquadratic growth (PQSQ).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The adaptive lasso was introduced by Zou in 2006 for linear regression and by Zhang and Lu in 2007 for proportional hazards regression.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The prior lasso was introduced for generalized linear models by Jiang et al. in 2016 to incorporate prior information, such as the importance of certain covariates.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In prior lasso, such information is summarized into pseudo responses (called prior responses) ${\hat {y}}^{\mathrm {p} }$ and then an additional criterion function is added to the usual objective function with a lasso penalty.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] the usual lasso objective function with the responses y being replaced by a weighted average of the observed responses and the prior responses ${\tilde {y}}=(y+\eta {\hat {y}}^{\mathrm {p} })/(1+\eta )$ (called the adjusted response values by the prior information).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In prior lasso, the parameter $\eta$ is called a balancing parameter, in that it balances the relative importance of the data and the prior information.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] In the extreme case of $\eta =0$ , prior lasso is reduced to lasso.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] If $\eta =\infty$ , prior lasso will solely rely on the prior information to fit the model.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Furthermore, the balancing parameter $\eta$ has another appealing interpretation: it controls the variance of $\beta$ in its prior distribution from a Bayesian viewpoint.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Prior lasso is more efficient in parameter estimation and prediction (with a smaller estimation error and prediction error) when the prior information is of high quality, and is robust to the low quality prior information with a good choice of the balancing parameter $\eta$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] This can be especially useful when the data is high-dimensional.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The procedure involves running lasso on each of several random subsets of the data and collating the results.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The loss function of the lasso is not differentiable, but a wide variety of techniques from convex analysis and optimization theory have been developed to compute the solutions path of the lasso.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] These include coordinate descent, subgradient methods, least-angle regression (LARS), and proximal gradient methods.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Subgradient methods are the natural generalization of traditional methods such as gradient descent and stochastic gradient descent to the case in which the objective function is not differentiable at all points.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] LARS is a method that is closely tied to lasso models, and in many cases allows them to be fit efficiently, though it may not perform well in all circumstances.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Proximal methods have become popular because of their flexibility and performance and are an area of active research.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The choice of method will depend on the particular lasso variant, the data and the available resources.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] However, proximal methods generally perform well.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The "glmnet" package in R, where "glm" is a reference to "generalized linear models" and "net" refers to the "net" from "elastic net" provides an extremely efficient way to implement LASSO and some of its variants.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The "celer" package in Python provides a highly efficient solver for the Lasso problem, often outperforming traditional solvers like scikit-learn by up to 100 times in certain scenarios, particularly with high-dimensional datasets.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] This package leverages dual extrapolation techniques to achieve its performance gains.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The celer package is available at GitHub.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Choosing the regularization parameter ( $\lambda$ ) is a fundamental part of lasso.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] A good value is essential to the performance of lasso since it controls the strength of shrinkage and variable selection, which, in moderation can improve both prediction accuracy and interpretability.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] However, if the regularization becomes too strong, important variables may be omitted and coefficients may be shrunk excessively, which can harm both predictive capacity and inferencing.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Cross-validation is often used to find the regularization parameter.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Information criteria such as the Bayesian information criterion (BIC) and the Akaike information criterion (AIC) might be preferable to cross-validation, because they are faster to compute and their performance is less volatile in small samples.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] An information criterion selects the estimator's regularization parameter by maximizing a model's in-sample accuracy while penalizing its effective number of parameters/degrees of freedom.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] Zou et al. proposed to measure the effective degrees of freedom by counting the number of parameters that deviate from zero.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] The degrees of freedom approach was considered flawed by Kaufman and Rosset and Janson et al., because a model's degrees of freedom might increase even when it is penalized harder by the regularization parameter.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] As an alternative, the relative simplicity measure defined above can be used to count the effective number of parameters.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] For the lasso, this measure is given by ${\hat {\mathcal {P}}}=\sum _{i=1}^{p}{\frac {|\beta _{i}-\beta _{0,i}|}{{\frac {1}{p}}\sum _{l}|b_{{\text{OLS}},l}-\beta _{0,l}|}},$ which monotonically increases from zero to p as the regularization parameter decreases from $\infty$ to zero.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/lasso-statistics] LASSO has been applied in economics and finance, and was found to improve prediction and to select sometimes neglected variables, for example in corporate bankruptcy prediction literature, or high growth firms prediction.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] In mathematics, statistics, finance, and computer science, particularly in machine learning and inverse problems, **regularization** is a process that converts the answer to a problem to a simpler one.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] It is often used in solving ill-posed problems or to prevent overfitting.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] There is a strong connection between regularization methods and Bayesian approaches for solving such ill-posed problems .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] In explicit regularization, independent of the problem or model, there is always a data term, that corresponds to a likelihood of the measurement, and a regularization term that corresponds to a prior.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] By combining both using Bayesian statistics, one can compute a posterior, that includes both information sources and therefore stabilizes the estimation process.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] By trading off both objectives, one chooses to be more aligned to the data or to enforce regularization (to prevent overfitting).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] There is a whole research branch dealing with all possible regularizations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] In practice, one usually tries a specific regularization and then figures out the probability density that corresponds to that regularization to justify the choice.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] It can also be physically motivated by common sense or intuition.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] In machine learning, the data term corresponds to the training data and the regularization is either the choice of the model or modifications to the algorithm.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] It is always intended to reduce the generalization error, i.e. the error score with the trained model on the evaluation set (testing data) and not the training data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] One of the earliest uses of regularization is Tikhonov regularization (ridge regression), related to the method of least squares.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] In machine learning, a key challenge is enabling models to accurately predict outcomes on unseen data, not just on familiar training data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Regularization is crucial for addressing overfitting—where a model memorizes training data details but cannot generalize to new data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The goal of regularization is to encourage models to learn the broader patterns within the data rather than memorizing it.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Techniques like early stopping, L1 and L2 regularization, and dropout are designed to prevent overfitting and underfitting, thereby enhancing the model's ability to adapt to and perform well with new data, thus improving model generalization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Stops training when validation performance deteriorates, preventing overfitting by halting before the model memorizes training data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] In the context of neural networks, the Dropout technique repeatedly ignores random subsets of neurons during training, which simulates the training of multiple neural network architectures at once to improve generalization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Empirical learning of classifiers (from a finite data set) is always an underdetermined problem, because it attempts to infer a function of any x given only examples $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Concrete notions of complexity used include restrictions for smoothness and bounds on the vector space norm.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] A theoretical justification for regularization is that it attempts to impose Occam's razor on the solution (as depicted in the figure above, where the green function, the simpler one, may be preferred).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] From a Bayesian point of view, many regularization techniques correspond to imposing certain prior distributions on model parameters.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Regularization can serve multiple purposes, including learning simpler models, inducing models to be sparse and introducing group structure into the learning problem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The same idea arose in many fields of science.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] A simple form of regularization applied to integral equations (Tikhonov regularization) is essentially a trade-off between fitting the data and reducing a norm of the solution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] More recently, non-linear regularization methods, including total variation regularization, have become popular.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Regularization can be motivated as a technique to improve the generalizability of a learned model.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The goal of this learning problem is to find a function that fits or predicts the outcome (label) that minimizes the expected error over all possible inputs and labels.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The expected error of a function $f_{n}$ is: $I[f_{n}]=\int _{X\times Y}V(f_{n}(x),y)\rho (x,y)\,dx\,dy$ where X and Y are the domains of input data x and their labels y respectively.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Typically in learning problems, only a subset of input data and labels are available, measured with some noise.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] If measurements (e.g. of $x_{i}$ ) were made with noise, this model may suffer from overfitting and display poor expected error.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Regularization introduces a penalty for exploring certain regions of the function space used to build the model, which can improve generalization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] These techniques are named for Andrey Nikolayevich Tikhonov, who applied regularization to integral equations and made important contributions in many other areas.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] When learning a linear function f , characterized by an unknown vector w such that $f(x)=w\cdot x$ , one can add the $L_{2}$ -norm of the vector w to the loss expression in order to prefer solutions with smaller norms.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Tikhonov regularization is one of the most common forms.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] As the $L_{2}$ norm is differentiable, learning can be advanced by gradient descent.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The learning problem with the least squares loss function and Tikhonov regularization can be solved analytically.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] By construction of the optimization problem, other values of w give larger values for the loss function.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This can be verified by examining the second derivative $\nabla _{ww}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] During training, this algorithm takes $O(d^{3}+nd^{2})$ time.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The terms correspond to the matrix inversion and calculating $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ , respectively.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Early stopping can be viewed as regularization in time.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Intuitively, a training procedure such as gradient descent tends to learn more and more complex functions with increasing iterations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] By regularizing for time, model complexity can be controlled, improving generalization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Early stopping is implemented using one data set for training, one statistically independent data set for validation and another for testing.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The model is trained until performance on the validation set no longer improves and then applied to the test set.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The exact solution to the unregularized least squares learning problem minimizes the empirical error, but may fail.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] By limiting T, the only free parameter in the algorithm above, the problem is regularized for time, which may improve its generalization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Enforcing a sparsity constraint on w can lead to simpler and more interpretable models.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This is useful in many real-life applications such as computational biology.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] An example is developing a simple predictive test for a disease in order to minimize the cost of performing medical tests while maximizing predictive power.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] A sensible sparsity constraint is the $L_{0}$ norm $\|w\|_{0}$ , defined as the number of non-zero elements in w .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Solving a $L_{0}$ regularized learning problem, however, has been demonstrated to be NP-hard.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The $L_{1}$ norm (see also Norms) can be used to approximate the optimal $L_{0}$ norm via convex relaxation.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] It can be shown that the $L_{1}$ norm induces sparsity.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] $L_{1}$ regularization can occasionally produce non-unique solutions.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] A simple example is provided in the figure when the space of possible solutions lies on a 45 degree line.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Elastic net regularization tends to have a grouping effect, where correlated input features are assigned equal weights.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Elastic net regularization is commonly used in practice and is implemented in many machine learning libraries.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] While the $L_{1}$ norm does not result in an NP-hard problem, the $L_{1}$ norm is convex but is not strictly differentiable due to the kink at x = 0.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Subgradient methods which rely on the subderivative can be used to solve $L_{1}$ regularized learning problems.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] However, faster convergence can be achieved through proximal methods.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] For a problem $\min _{w\in H}F(w)+R(w)$ such that F is convex, continuous, differentiable, with Lipschitz continuous gradient (such as the least squares loss function), and R is convex, continuous, and proper, then the proximal method to solve the problem is as follows.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The proximal method iteratively performs gradient descent and then projects the result back into the space permitted by R .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Groups of features can be regularized by a sparsity constraint, which can be useful for expressing certain prior knowledge into an optimization problem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This can be viewed as inducing a regularizer over the $L_{2}$ norm over members of each group followed by an $L_{1}$ norm over groups.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The algorithm described for group sparsity without overlaps can be applied to the case where groups do overlap, in certain situations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This will likely result in some groups with all zero elements, and other groups with some non-zero and some zero elements.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] For each $w_{g}$ , ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ is defined as the vector such that the restriction of ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ to the group g equals $w_{g}$ and all other entries of ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ are zero.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The regularizer finds the optimal disintegration of w into parts.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] It can be viewed as duplicating all elements that exist in multiple groups.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Learning problems with this regularizer can also be solved with the proximal method with a complication.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The proximal operator cannot be computed in closed form, but can be effectively solved iteratively, inducing an inner iteration within the proximal method iteration.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] When labels are more expensive to gather than input examples, semi-supervised learning can be useful.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Regularizers have been designed to guide learning algorithms to learn models that respect the structure of unsupervised training samples.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] If $W_{ij}$ encodes the result of some distance metric for points $x_{i}$ and $x_{j}$ , it is desirable that $f(x_{i})\approx f(x_{j})$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer captures this intuition, and is equivalent to: $R(f)={\bar {f}}^{\mathsf {T}}L{\bar {f}}$ where $L=D-W$ is the Laplacian matrix of the graph induced by W .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The optimization problem $\min _{f\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}}R(f),m=u+l$ can be solved analytically if the constraint $f(x_{i})=y_{i}$ is applied for all supervised samples.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The labeled part of the vector f is therefore obvious.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] In the case of multitask learning, T problems are considered simultaneously, each related in some way.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The goal is to learn T functions, ideally borrowing strength from the relatedness of tasks, that have predictive power.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This is equivalent to learning the matrix $W:T\times D$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer defines an L2 norm on each column and an L1 norm over all columns.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] $R(w)=\left\|\sigma (W)\right\|_{1}$ where $\sigma (W)$ is the eigenvalues in the singular value decomposition of W .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer constrains the functions learned for each task to be similar to the overall average of the functions across all tasks.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This is useful for expressing prior information that each task is expected to share with each other task.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] An example is predicting blood iron levels measured at different times of the day, where each task represents an individual.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer is similar to the mean-constrained regularizer, but instead enforces similarity between tasks within the same cluster.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This can capture more complex prior information.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] This technique has been used to predict Netflix recommendations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] A cluster would correspond to a group of people who share similar preferences.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] More generally than above, similarity between tasks can be defined by a function.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] The regularizer encourages the model to learn similar functions for similar tasks. $R(f_{1}\cdots f_{T})=\sum _{t,s=1,t\neq s}^{\mathsf {T}}\left\|f_{t}-f_{s}\right\|^{2}M_{ts}$ for a given symmetric similarity matrix M .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Bayesian learning methods make use of a prior probability that (usually) gives lower probability to more complex models.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Well-known model selection techniques include the Akaike information criterion (AIC), minimum description length (MDL), and the Bayesian information criterion (BIC).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularization-mathematics] Alternative methods of controlling overfitting not involving regularization include cross-validation.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The first comes up when the number of variables in the linear system exceeds the number of observations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In such settings, the ordinary least-squares problem is ill-posed and is therefore impossible to fit because the associated optimization problem has infinitely many solutions.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] RLS allows the introduction of further constraints that uniquely determine the solution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The second reason for using RLS arises when the learned model suffers from poor generalization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] RLS can be used in such cases to improve the generalizability of the model by constraining it at training time.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This constraint can either force the solution to be "sparse" in some way or to reflect other prior knowledge about the problem such as information about correlations between features.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] A Bayesian understanding of this can be reached by showing that RLS methods are often equivalent to priors on the solution to the least-squares problem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Consider a learning setting given by a probabilistic space $(X\times Y,\rho (X,Y))$ , $Y\in R$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Let $S=\{x_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}$ denote a training set of n pairs i.i.d. with respect to the joint distribution $\rho$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Let $V:Y\times R\to [0;\infty )$ be a loss function.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Define F as the space of the functions such that expected risk: $\varepsilon (f)=\int V(y,f(x))\,d\rho (x,y)$ is well defined.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The main goal is to minimize the expected risk: $\inf _{f\in F}\varepsilon (f)$ Since the problem cannot be solved exactly there is a need to specify how to measure the quality of a solution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] A good learning algorithm should provide an estimator with a small risk.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] As the joint distribution $\rho$ is typically unknown, the empirical risk is taken.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] However, if the functions are from a relatively unconstrained space, such as the set of square-integrable functions on X , this approach may overfit the training data, and lead to poor generalization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Thus, it should somehow constrain or penalize the complexity of the function f .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] A RKHS can be defined by a symmetric positive-definite kernel function $K(x,z)$ with the reproducing property: $\langle K_{x},f\rangle _{\mathcal {H}}=f(x),$ where $K_{x}(z)=K(x,z)$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The RKHS for a kernel K consists of the completion of the space of functions spanned by $\left\{K_{x}\mid x\in X\right\}$ : ${\textstyle f(x)=\sum _{i=1}^{n}\alpha _{i}K_{x_{i}}(x),\,f\in {\mathcal {H}}}$ , where all $\alpha _{i}$ are real numbers.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Note that for an arbitrary loss function V , this approach defines a general class of algorithms named Tikhonov regularization.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] For instance, using the hinge loss leads to the support vector machine algorithm, and using the epsilon-insensitive loss leads to support vector regression.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The representer theorem guarantees that the solution can be written as: $f(x)=\sum _{i=1}^{n}c_{i}K(x_{i},x)$ for some $c\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The complexity of training is basically the cost of computing the kernel matrix plus the cost of solving the linear system which is roughly $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The computation of the kernel matrix for the linear or Gaussian kernel is $O(n^{2}D)$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] For convenience a vector notation is introduced.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Let X be an $n\times d$ matrix, where the rows are input vectors, and Y a $n\times 1$ vector where the entries are corresponding outputs.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In terms of vectors, the kernel matrix can be written as $K=XX^{\mathsf {T}}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The first term is the objective function from ordinary least squares (OLS) regression, corresponding to the residual sum of squares.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The second term is a regularization term, not present in OLS, which penalizes large w values.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] As a smooth finite dimensional problem is considered and it is possible to apply standard calculus tools.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This solution closely resembles that of standard linear regression, with an extra term $\lambda I$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] If the assumptions of OLS regression hold, the solution $w=\left(X^{\mathsf {T}}X\right)^{-1}X^{\mathsf {T}}y$ , with $\lambda =0$ , is an unbiased estimator, and is the minimum-variance linear unbiased estimator, according to the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The term $\lambda nI$ therefore leads to a biased solution; however, it also tends to reduce variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This is easy to see, as the covariance matrix of the w -values is proportional to $\left(X^{\mathsf {T}}X+\lambda nI\right)^{-1}$ , and therefore large values of $\lambda$ will lead to lower variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Therefore, manipulating $\lambda$ corresponds to trading-off bias and variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] For problems with high-variance w estimates, such as cases with relatively small n or with correlated regressors, the optimal prediction accuracy may be obtained by using a nonzero $\lambda$ , and thus introducing some bias to reduce variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Furthermore, it is not uncommon in machine learning to have cases where $n<d$ , in which case $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ is rank-deficient, and a nonzero $\lambda$ is necessary to compute $\left(X^{\mathsf {T}}X+\lambda nI\right)^{-1}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The parameter $\lambda$ controls the invertibility of the matrix $X^{\mathsf {T}}X+\lambda nI$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Several methods can be used to solve the above linear system, Cholesky decomposition being probably the method of choice, since the matrix $X^{\mathsf {T}}X+\lambda nI$ is symmetric and positive definite.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The complexity of this method is $O(nD^{2})$ for training and $O(D)$ for testing.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The cost $O(nD^{2})$ is essentially that of computing $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ , whereas the inverse computation (or rather the solution of the linear system) is roughly $O(D^{3})$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In this section it will be shown how to extend RLS to any kind of reproducing kernel K.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Instead of linear kernel a feature map is considered $\Phi :X\to F$ for some Hilbert space F , called the feature space.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This approach is known as the kernel trick.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This technique can significantly simplify the computational operations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] If F is high dimensional, computing $\varphi (x_{i})$ may be rather intensive.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] If the explicit form of the kernel function is known, we just need to compute and store the $n\times n$ kernel matrix K .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In fact, the Hilbert space F need not be isomorphic to $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , and can be infinite dimensional.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This follows from Mercer's theorem, which states that a continuous, symmetric, positive definite kernel function can be expressed as $K(x,z)=\sum _{i=1}^{\infty }\sigma _{i}e_{i}(x)e_{i}(z)$ where $e_{i}(x)$ form an orthonormal basis for $\ell ^{2}(X)$ , and $\sigma _{i}\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] If feature maps is defined $\varphi (x)$ with components $\varphi _{i}(x)={\sqrt {\sigma _{i}}}e_{i}(x)$ , it follows that $K(x,z)=\langle \varphi (x),\varphi (z)\rangle$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This demonstrates that any kernel can be associated with a feature map, and that RLS generally consists of linear RLS performed in some possibly higher-dimensional feature space.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] While Mercer's theorem shows how one feature map that can be associated with a kernel, in fact multiple feature maps can be associated with a given reproducing kernel.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] For instance, the map $\varphi (x)=K_{x}$ satisfies the property $K(x,z)=\langle \varphi (x),\varphi (z)\rangle$ for an arbitrary reproducing kernel.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Least squares can be viewed as a likelihood maximization under an assumption of normally distributed residuals.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This is because the exponent of the Gaussian distribution is quadratic in the data, and so is the least-squares objective function.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In this framework, the regularization terms of RLS can be understood to be encoding priors on w .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] For instance, Tikhonov regularization corresponds to a normally distributed prior on w that is centered at 0.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] To see this, first note that the OLS objective is proportional to the log-likelihood function when each sampled $y^{i}$ is normally distributed around $w^{\mathsf {T}}\cdot x^{i}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Then observe that a normal prior on w centered at 0 has a log-probability of the form $\log P(w)=q-\alpha \sum _{j=1}^{d}w_{j}^{2}$ where q and $\alpha$ are constants that depend on the variance of the prior and are independent of w .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Thus, minimizing the logarithm of the likelihood times the prior is equivalent to minimizing the sum of the OLS loss function and the ridge regression regularization term.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Other regularization methods correspond to different priors.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The following is a list of possible choices of the regularization function $R(\cdot )$ , along with the name for each one, the corresponding prior if there is a simple one, and ways for computing the solution to the resulting optimization problem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] When $\lambda =0$ , i.e., in the case of ordinary least squares, the condition that $d>n$ causes the sample covariance matrix ${\frac {1}{n}}X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ to not have full rank and so it cannot be inverted to yield a unique solution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This is why there can be an infinitude of solutions to the ordinary least squares problem when $d>n$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] However, when $\lambda >0$ , i.e., when ridge regression is used, the addition of $\lambda I$ to the sample covariance matrix ensures that all of its eigenvalues will be strictly greater than 0.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In other words, it becomes invertible, and the solution is then unique.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Compared to ordinary least squares, ridge regression is not unbiased.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] It accepts bias to reduce variance and the mean square error.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This algorithm, for automatic (as opposed to heuristic) regularization, is obtained as a fixed point solution in the maximum likelihood estimation of the parameters.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Although the guarantees of convergence are not provided, the examples indicate that a satisfactory solution may be obtained after a couple of iterations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Thus, while it can be used without problems for $n>d$ caution is recommended for $n<d$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] The least absolute selection and shrinkage (LASSO) method is another popular choice.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Note that the lasso penalty function is convex but not strictly convex.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Unlike Tikhonov regularization, this scheme does not have a convenient closed-form solution: instead, the solution is typically found using quadratic programming or more general convex optimization methods, as well as by specific algorithms such as the least-angle regression algorithm.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] An important difference between lasso regression and Tikhonov regularization is that lasso regression forces more entries of w to actually equal 0 than would otherwise.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In contrast, while Tikhonov regularization forces entries of w to be small, it does not force more of them to be 0 than would be otherwise.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Thus, LASSO regularization is more appropriate than Tikhonov regularization in cases in which we expect the number of non-zero entries of w to be small, and Tikhonov regularization is more appropriate when we expect that entries of w will generally be small but not necessarily zero.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Which of these regimes is more relevant depends on the specific data set at hand.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Besides feature selection described above, LASSO has some limitations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Ridge regression provides better accuracy in the case $n>d$ for highly correlated variables.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In another case, $n<d$ , LASSO selects at most n variables.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Moreover, LASSO tends to select some arbitrary variables from group of highly correlated samples, so there is no grouping effect.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This corresponds to setting $R(w)$ to be the $\ell _{0}$ norm of w .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] This regularization function, while attractive for the sparsity that it guarantees, is very difficult to solve because doing so requires optimization of a function that is not even weakly convex.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Lasso regression is the minimal possible relaxation of $\ell _{0}$ penalization that yields a weakly convex optimization problem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] Consider $(1-\alpha )\left\|w\right\|_{1}+\alpha \left\|w\right\|_{2}\leq t$ as an Elastic Net penalty function.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] One of the main properties of the Elastic Net is that it can select groups of correlated variables.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] If $x_{i}$ and $x_{j}$ are highly correlated ( $\rho _{ij}\to 1$ ), the weight vectors are very close.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] In the case of negatively correlated samples ( $\rho _{ij}\to -1$ ) the samples $-x_{j}$ can be taken.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/regularized-least-squares] To summarize, for highly correlated variables the weight vectors tend to be equal up to a sign in the case of negative correlated variables.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] In statistics, **shrinkage** is the reduction in the effects of sampling variation.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] In regression analysis, a fitted relationship appears to perform less well on a new data set than on the data set used for fitting.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] In particular the value of the coefficient of determination 'shrinks'.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] A **shrinkage estimator** is an estimator that, either explicitly or implicitly, incorporates the effects of shrinkage.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] In loose terms this means that a naive or raw estimate is improved by combining it with other information.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] The term relates to the notion that the improved estimate is made closer to the value supplied by the 'other information' than the raw estimate.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] In this sense, shrinkage is used to regularize ill-posed inference problems.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] Shrinkage is implicit in Bayesian inference and penalized likelihood inference, and explicit in James–Stein-type inference.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] In contrast, simple types of maximum-likelihood and least-squares estimation procedures do not include shrinkage effects, although they can be used within shrinkage estimation schemes.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] Many standard estimators can be improved, in terms of mean squared error (MSE), by shrinking them towards zero (or any other finite constant value).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] In other words, the improvement in the estimate from the corresponding reduction in the width of the confidence interval can outweigh the worsening of the estimate introduced by biasing the estimate towards zero (see bias-variance tradeoff).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] Assume that the expected value of the raw estimate is not zero and consider other estimators obtained by multiplying the raw estimate by a certain parameter.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] A value for this parameter can be specified so as to minimize the MSE of the new estimate.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] For this value of the parameter, the new estimate will have a smaller MSE than the raw one, and thus it has been improved.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] An effect here may be to convert an unbiased raw estimate to an improved biased one.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] An example arises in the estimation of the population variance by sample variance.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] For a sample size of *n*, the use of a divisor *n*−1 in the usual formula (Bessel's correction) gives an unbiased estimator, while other divisors have lower MSE, at the expense of bias.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] The use of shrinkage estimators in the context of regression analysis, where there may be a large number of explanatory variables, has been described by Copas.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] Here the values of the estimated regression coefficients are shrunk towards zero with the effect of reducing the mean square error of predicted values from the model when applied to new data.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] A later paper by Copas applies shrinkage in a context where the problem is to predict a binary response on the basis of binary explanatory variables.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] Hausser and Strimmer "develop a James-Stein-type shrinkage estimator, resulting in a procedure that is highly efficient statistically as well as computationally.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] Despite its simplicity, it outperforms eight other entropy estimation procedures across a diverse range of sampling scenarios and data-generating models, even in cases of severe undersampling. ... method is fully analytic and hence computationally inexpensive.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] Moreover, procedure simultaneously provides estimates of the entropy and of the cell frequencies.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/shrinkage-statistics] The proposed shrinkage estimators of entropy and mutual information, as well as all other investigated entropy estimators, have been implemented in R (R Development Core Team, 2008).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] The theory was first introduced by Hoerl and Kennard in 1970 in their *Technometrics* papers "Ridge regressions: biased estimation of nonorthogonal problems" and "Ridge regressions: applications in nonorthogonal problems".
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Ridge regression was developed as a possible solution to the imprecision of least square estimators when linear regression models have some multicollinear (highly correlated) independent variables—by creating a ridge regression estimator (RR).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] This provides a more precise ridge parameters estimate, as its variance and mean square estimator are often smaller than the least square estimators previously derived.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] the problem of a near-singular moment matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X}$ is alleviated by adding positive elements to the diagonals, thereby decreasing its condition number.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In fact, there is a one-to-one relationship between c and $\lambda$ and since, in practice, we do not know c , we define $\lambda$ heuristically or find it via additional data-fitting strategies, see Determination of the Tikhonov parameter below.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] The optimal regularization parameter $\lambda$ is usually unknown and in practice needs to be estimated.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Typically, a data-driven choice for the Tikhonov regularization parameter $\lambda$ is accomplished either via cross-validation, or via a plug-in procedure, as follows.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] A common data-driven choice for $\lambda$ is the minimizer of the cross-validation loss or its generalizations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Assume that $\mathbf {X}$ is an $n\times p$ matrix and define the matrix $\Omega :=(\mathbf {X} ^{\top }\mathbf {X} /n)^{+}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] where $\varsigma ^{2}$ is the variance of the noise ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}=\mathbf {Y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ , that is, $\mathrm {Var} ({\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }})=\varsigma ^{2}\mathbf {I}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] It can be shown that the ridge estimator ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}_{\lambda ^{*}}$ enjoys smaller expected in-sample risk than the minimum-norm least-squares estimator ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}_{0}=\mathbf {X} ^{+}\mathbf {Y}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] where the expectations treat $\mathbf {X}$ as fixed and $\mathbf {Y} '$ is *test response* data, independent from $\mathbf {Y}$ (and hence independent from the estimators ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}_{0}$ and ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}_{\lambda ^{*}}$ ).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Of course, in practice the formula for $\lambda ^{*}$ is used by plugging in statistical estimators for the unknown parameters ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ and $\varsigma ^{2}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Alternative approaches to the data-driven selection of the Tikhonov regularization parameter include the discrepancy principle, L-curve method, restricted maximum likelihood.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Tikhonov regularization was invented independently in many different contexts.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] It became widely known through its application to integral equations in the works of Andrey Tikhonov and David L.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Some authors use the term **Tikhonov–Phillips regularization**.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] The finite-dimensional case was expounded by Arthur E.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Hoerl, who took a statistical approach, and by Manus Foster, who interpreted this method as a Wiener–Kolmogorov (Kriging) filter.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Following Hoerl, it is known in the statistical literature as ridge regression, named after ridge analysis ("ridge" refers to the path from the constrained maximum).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Suppose that for a known real matrix A and vector $\mathbf {b}$ , we wish to find a vector $\mathbf {x}$ such that $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b} ,$ where $\mathbf {x}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ may be of different sizes and A may even be non-square.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] The standard approach is ordinary least squares linear regression.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] However, if no $\mathbf {x}$ satisfies the equation or more than one $\mathbf {x}$ does—that is, the solution is not unique—the problem is said to be ill posed.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In such cases, ordinary least squares estimation leads to an overdetermined, or more often an underdetermined system of equations.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Most real-world phenomena have the effect of low-pass filters in the forward direction where A maps $\mathbf {x}$ to $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Therefore, in solving the inverse-problem, the inverse mapping operates as a high-pass filter that has the undesirable tendency of amplifying noise (eigenvalues / singular values are largest in the reverse mapping where they were smallest in the forward mapping).
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In addition, ordinary least squares implicitly nullifies every element of the reconstructed version of $\mathbf {x}$ that is in the null-space of A , rather than allowing for a model to be used as a prior for $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Ordinary least squares seeks to minimize the sum of squared residuals, which can be compactly written as $\left\|A\mathbf {x} -\mathbf {b} \right\|_{2}^{2},$ where $\|\cdot \|_{2}$ is the Euclidean norm.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In many cases, this matrix is chosen as a scalar multiple of the identity matrix ( $\Gamma =\alpha I$ ), giving preference to solutions with smaller norms; this is known as ***L*2 regularization**.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In other cases, high-pass operators (e.g., a difference operator or a weighted Fourier operator) may be used to enforce smoothness if the underlying vector is believed to be mostly continuous.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] This regularization improves the conditioning of the problem, thus enabling a direct numerical solution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] For $\Gamma =0$ this reduces to the unregularized least-squares solution, provided that (*A*T*A*)−1 exists.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Note that in case of a complex matrix A , as usual the transpose $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ has to be replaced by the Hermitian transpose $A^{\mathsf {H}}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Since Tikhonov Regularization simply adds a quadratic term to the objective function in optimization problems, it is possible to do so after the unregularised optimisation has taken place.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In the context of arbitrary likelihood fits, this is valid, as long as the quadratic approximation of the likelihood function is valid.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] This means that, as long as the perturbation from the unregularised result is small, one can regularise any result that is presented as a best fit point with a covariance matrix.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] No detailed knowledge of the underlying likelihood function is needed.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] For general multivariate normal distributions for $\mathbf {x}$ and the data error, one can apply a transformation of the variables to reduce to the case above.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In the Bayesian interpretation P is the inverse covariance matrix of $\mathbf {b}$ , $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ is the expected value of $\mathbf {x}$ , and Q is the inverse covariance matrix of $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] The Tikhonov matrix is not explicitly included because the corresponding regularization term $\left\|\Gamma \mathbf {x} -\mathbf {x} _{0}'\right\|_{Q'}^{2}$ reduces to above with $\Gamma \mathbf {x} _{0}=\mathbf {x} _{0}'$ and $Q=\Gamma ^{T}Q'\Gamma$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] For normal regularization where $Q'=I$ , the Tikhonov matrix then appears in the Cholesky factorization $Q=\Gamma ^{\mathsf {T}}\Gamma$ and is considered a whitening filter.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In some situations, one can avoid using the transpose $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ , as proposed by Mikhail Lavrentyev.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Typically discrete linear ill-conditioned problems result from discretization of integral equations, and one can formulate a Tikhonov regularization in the original infinite-dimensional context.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In the above we can interpret A as a compact operator on Hilbert spaces, and x and b as elements in the domain and range of A .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] The operator $A^{*}A+\Gamma ^{\mathsf {T}}\Gamma$ is then a self-adjoint bounded invertible operator.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] With $\Gamma =\alpha I$ , this least-squares solution can be analyzed in a special way using the singular-value decomposition.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] This demonstrates the effect of the Tikhonov parameter on the condition number of the regularized problem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] For the generalized case, a similar representation can be derived using a generalized singular-value decomposition.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] The probabilistic formulation of an inverse problem introduces (when all uncertainties are Gaussian) a covariance matrix $C_{M}$ representing the *a priori* uncertainties on the model parameters, and a covariance matrix $C_{D}$ representing the uncertainties on the observed parameters.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] In the special case when these two matrices are diagonal and isotropic, $C_{M}=\sigma _{M}^{2}I$ and $C_{D}=\sigma _{D}^{2}I$ , and, in this case, the equations of inverse theory reduce to the equations above, with $\alpha ={\sigma _{D}}/{\sigma _{M}}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Although at first the choice of the solution to this regularized problem may look artificial, and indeed the matrix $\Gamma$ seems rather arbitrary, the process can be justified from a Bayesian point of view.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Note that for an ill-posed problem one must necessarily introduce some additional assumptions in order to get a unique solution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Statistically, the prior probability distribution of x is sometimes taken to be a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] For simplicity here, the following assumptions are made: the means are zero; their components are independent; the components have the same standard deviation $\sigma _{x}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] The data are also subject to errors, and the errors in b are also assumed to be independent with zero mean and standard deviation $\sigma _{b}$ .
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] Under these assumptions the Tikhonov-regularized solution is the most probable solution given the data and the *a priori* distribution of x , according to Bayes' theorem.
[src:ridge-lasso-regression/tikhonov-regularization] If the assumption of normality is replaced by assumptions of homoscedasticity and uncorrelatedness of errors, and if one still assumes zero mean, then the Gauss–Markov theorem entails that the solution is the minimal unbiased linear estimator.
